It's difficult to predict exactly when you may start feeling better with MS, as the progression of the disease and response to treatment can vary greatly from person to person. However, here are some general guidelines on what you might expect in terms of improvement over time:
1. Acute relapses: If you experience an acute relapse, symptoms usually peak within 2-4 weeks and then gradually improve over several weeks or months. During this time, your healthcare provider may prescribe medication to reduce inflammation and manage symptoms.
2. Disease-modifying therapies (DMTs): These medications are designed to slow the progression of disability and reduce the frequency and severity of relapses. They typically take several months to a year or more to show their full effects. Improvement may be subtle at first but can accumulate over time. DMTs work best for people who begin treatment early in the course of their disease, so it's essential to talk to your doctor about starting these medications as soon as possible if they become available.
