There are several reading problems that can be associated with multiple sclerosis (MS). Here are some of the most common ones:
1. Difficulty with speed reading: People with MS may find it hard to read quickly and smoothly, as their eyes may feel heavy or tired easily.
2. Blurred vision: Some people with MS experience blurred vision, which can make it difficult to focus on text and affect their ability to read clearly.
3. Eye movement difficulties: MS can cause weakness, numbness, or spasticity in the muscles that control eye movements, making it challenging for individuals to move their eyes left to right, up and down, or track text while reading;
4. Double vision: In some cases, MS can cause double vision or diplopia, which can make reading more complicated due to the presence of two images instead of one;
5. Reading comprehension issues: Fatigue, cognitive impairment, and depression can all contribute to difficulty with reading comprehension in individuals with MS;
6. Visual processing deficits: MS can affect the way visual information is processed in the brain, leading to difficulties with recognizing and understanding written words and sentences.
